						</outline>
					<outline text="&lt;i&gt;Update: They changed their OPML, now it implements the spec, as far as I can see. My software can process the format. I think they should download the file to the user's computer like everyone else does.&lt;/i&gt;" created="Sun, 30 Jun 2013 19:27:53 GMT" pgfnum="27478"/>
					<outline text="I got an email from a friend with a pointer to an &lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.feedly.com/2013/06/29/opml-export/&quot;&gt;announcement&lt;/a&gt; from Feedly that they now support OPML export. " created="Sun, 30 Jun 2013 17:35:43 GMT" pgfnum="27453"/>
					<outline text="It's true, in a way, they do. However there's a &lt;a href=&quot;http://dev.opml.org/spec2.html#subscriptionLists&quot;&gt;spec that explains&lt;/a&gt; how a &lt;i&gt;subscription list&lt;/i&gt; works, and theirs does not comply with the spec. You could not use their OPML to import it into my tools, and I don't believe it would work anywhere else either." created="Sun, 30 Jun 2013 17:36:05 GMT" pgfnum="27454"/>
					<outline text="Also they produce the OPML in a &lt;a href=&quot;http://static.scripting.com/larryKing/images/2013/06/30/feedlyOpml.gif&quot;&gt;bizarre way&lt;/a&gt;. Why not just download the file to the users' computer as an OPML file? It's not hard to figure out. We do it in &lt;a href=&quot;http://littleoutliner.com/&quot;&gt;Little Outliner&lt;/a&gt;. They could just do it the way we do it. View source to see. ;-)" created="Sun, 30 Jun 2013 17:40:08 GMT" pgfnum="27456"/>
					<outline text="Here's a link to an &lt;a href=&quot;http://static.scripting.com/river3/opml/nytRiver.opml&quot;&gt;OPML subscription list&lt;/a&gt; that's properly arranged." created="Sun, 30 Jun 2013 17:40:55 GMT" pgfnum="27457"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Blogger vs Journalist" created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:44:56 GMT" name="bloggerVsJournalist" pgfnum="27327" type="thread">
					<outline text="&lt;rules&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 20:16:53 GMT" pgfnum="4929">
						<outline text="&lt;rule&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:33 GMT" pgfnum="4925">
							<outline text="&lt;font-family&gt;Georgia&lt;/font-family&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:43 GMT" pgfnum="4926"/>
							<outline text="&lt;font-size&gt;18px&lt;/font-size&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:43 GMT" pgfnum="4926"/>
							<outline text="&lt;line-height&gt;150%&lt;/line-height&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:43 GMT" pgfnum="4926"/>
							<outline text="&lt;/rule&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:53 GMT" pgfnum="4927"/>
							</outline>
						<outline text="&lt;/rules&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 20:16:55 GMT" pgfnum="4930"/>
						</outline>
					<outline text="Margaret Sullivan, &lt;a href=&quot;http://publiceditor.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/29/whos-a-journalist-a-question-with-many-facets-and-one-sure-answer/&quot;&gt;writing&lt;/a&gt; at the NY Times, tries to define what a journalist is, in the age of blogging." created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:45:02 GMT" pgfnum="27328"/>
					<outline text="I've been thinking and writing about this for a long time." created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:45:33 GMT" pgfnum="27329"/>
					<outline text="When I started at Berkman in 2003, with the mission to start the blogging activity at Harvard, possibly the first at an academic institution anywhere, one of the first questions I tried to answer is &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/whatmakesaweblogaweblog.html&quot;&gt;What makes a weblog a weblog?&lt;/a&gt; " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:45:42 GMT" pgfnum="27330"/>
					<outline text="The conclusion I came to is that it's the &lt;i&gt;unedited voice of an individual.&lt;/i&gt; The medium and form is not important. You could write a blog post in print on the op-ed page of the Times. But as soon as another person is involved in the writing of the piece, we're not talking about a blog anymore. " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:46:29 GMT" pgfnum="27331"/>
					<outline text="The process continued over the years. " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:47:23 GMT" pgfnum="27332"/>
					<outline text="In &lt;a href=&quot;http://rebootnews.wordpress.com/&quot;&gt;podcasts&lt;/a&gt; with Jay Rosen, we talked about this a lot. Jay is a well-known journalism professor at NYU. I of course, am a blogger. " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:47:35 GMT" pgfnum="27333"/>
					<outline text="In that period I came up with this idea. Bloggers are what journalists call &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/stories/2009/03/19/theRebootOfJournalism.html&quot;&gt;sources&lt;/a&gt;. Originators of information or ideas. People who make news, and not people who report news.  " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:48:05 GMT" pgfnum="27334"/>
					<outline text="I think that distinction is very important when trying to decide who has the official shield of a journalist, protected from government prosecution when leaks are involved. As long as the person is reporting the news, and not making the news, then we're clearly talking about a journalist and not a blogger. " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:49:08 GMT" pgfnum="27335"/>
					<outline text="If this is what a journalist is, then Glenn Greenwald was most definitely a journalist when reporting the Snowden story, as long as all he did was report on the leaks. If he himself leaked, then he is a blogger. " created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:55:25 GMT" pgfnum="27337"/>
					<outline text="Hope this helps." created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:50:10 GMT" pgfnum="27336"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Write a blog post with Fargo" created="Sat, 29 Jun 2013 20:28:20 GMT" name="writeABlogPostWithFargo" pgfnum="27322" type="thread">
					<outline text="&lt;rules&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 20:16:53 GMT" pgfnum="4929">
						<outline text="&lt;rule&gt;" created="Sat, 04 Feb 2012 19:09:33 GMT" pgfnum="4925">
